[2]
Date: Mon 10 Dec 2012
Source: JSonline, Milwaukee-Wisconsin Journal Sentinel [edited]
http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/sports/182891541.html


A deer from outside the chronic wasting disease management zone in Grant County has tested positive for the disease, according to a statement released Monday [10 Dec 2012] by the Department of Natural Resources [DNR].

The 2.5-year-old buck was killed and registered 18 Nov 2012. "It's disappointing but not unexpected to have a CWD-positive outside the current zone boundary," said DNR wildlife supervisor Don Bates in the statement. "This is why we have focused surveillance around the fringes of the CWD management zone, to better understand the distribution of the disease and identify the presence of the disease in periphery areas."

The CWD-positive deer was killed about 6 miles [9.7 km] outside the border of the CWD management zone and about 8 miles [13 km] from the nearest positive. This is the 2nd year the DNR has focused surveillance around the boundaries of the existing CWD management zone. Sampling of deer is voluntary in these areas and in Grant County, DNR partners with taxidermists to collect samples.

The DNR's CWD-sampling goal for 2012 is 4200 deer in southern Wisconsin and 1000 deer near Shell Lake, according to the agency. Most of the samples were obtained during the gun deer hunting season, which ran 17-25 Nov 2012.

Testing for the disease is conducted at the University of Wisconsin Veterinary Diagnostic Laboratory in Madison. Test results are typically available in 21 days.

CWD is a neurological disease caused by a misfolded prion or protein. The disease is contagious and fatal to deer, elk, and moose. It has not been shown to affect the health of humans or livestock.

The disease was first documented in the 1960s in western states. It was discovered in Wisconsin in 2002.

CWD was found only in southern Wisconsin until November 2011 when a CWD-positive deer was found near Shell Lake in northwestern Wisconsin.

The CWD-positive finding in Grant County does not change any remaining hunting seasons nor does it change the current CWD management zone boundary, according to the DNR. Baiting and feeding of deer is already banned in the county and will continue to be illegal.

[Byline: Paul A Smith]

